title: Photoneutron cross section of F-19.

x4freetext: Photoneutron cross section of F-19.

x4codes.hlp: National Research Council, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada
National Research Council, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada

x4freetext: The teflon (C2F4) target was 6 in.  diam.  by  6  in.
long.
The neutron detector  consisted  of  a  30  cm
diam.   by   15  cm  thick  disc  of  NE102  plastic
scintillator viewed by four 56 AVP phototubes.
At each  end-point energy the bremsstrahlung spectrum
was  determined  from   a   deuterium   photoneutron
spectrum.   The   photoneutron   cross  section  was
obtained from the efficiency-corrected  photoneutron
spectra  which  were  divided  by the bremsstrahlung
intensity distributions.
No information about sources of uncertainties.
The data were corrected for
(a) the background and
(b) the detector efficiency.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Annals of Physics (New York), Vol.27, p.79 (1964)

x4freetext: Photoneutron energy spectra  from  F-19  produced  by
bremsstrahlung  at  1 MeV end-point energy intervals
between  13  and   21   MeV   were   measured.   The
ground-state  and  the  excited-state cross sections
were derived from the neutron spectra.
By compiler :  data were read from  the  solid  curve
with  the  constant step by the compiler.  The solid
curve was obtained by the authors.
The total cross section of photoneutron  reaction  on
F-19  is 30 MeV*mb between threshold (10.43 MeV) and
19  MeV,   that   represents   about   8%   of   the
exchangeaugmented dipole sum.

x4freetext: The total photoneutron  cross  section  reported  by

sum of  ground-state  and  the  excited-state  cross
sections of present work.
Data  were  compiled  in SCJAD of Saratov
State University.

x4freetext: The excitation energy after neutron emission.
From the  family  of excited-state spectra which were
obtained as a difference of the total neutron energy
spectra  and  the  ground-state  neutron spectra the
excited-state cross section for all neutrons feeding
the four states of F-18 at about 1.04 MeV excitation
was found.
The ratio  of  the excited-state cross section to the
ground-state cross section is about 5 to 1.
Data from Fig. 1 of 73PACIFI,,167,1973.
